06 April 2015
07 March 2026

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
(1a) Compiling

./compile_all_Linux_gfortran.sh

and away you go.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
(2) Installation

Copy all the executable files into a subdirectory and put the subdirectory
in your path.  Run the program from the system prompt.

That is it.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
(3) Running

In the archive, you should find a /Simple_Simn directory.  It contains all the 
files you need to run a very simple simulation, then calculate the diffuse
scattering in three reciprocal space basal planes.

Below is a minimal session running ZMC from the command line.

(1) We run ZMC ($ indicates the command prompt).  
The input file is MC_keywords.inp, 
the output goes to Test1.extension, and the --diffuse flag means it is in a 
format suitable for the DZMC program.

(2) Then we run DZMC to produce the diffuse scattering, with the output going 
into hk0_Test1 given that we are calculating the hk0 cut.

(3) Then we convert the resulting binary file to a portable grey map (pgm) using bin2gray.

NOTES:

* The files below use very few MC cycles and very few lots; this is to make the 
example fast, it does _not_ result in a useful simulation.

** ZMC --help and ZMC --help2 both give some assistance.  Also bin2gray --help

*** Other toolbox programs (zmat_maker, for example) are included, please 
refer to their --help output.

**** MOST IMPORTANT: This is _not_ production-ready software.  It is a toolbox 
made by one scientist for his own use, and may have infelicities and problems.  
I am happy to enter a dialogue about this (goossens@rsc.anu.edu.au) but please 
remember I am one man and cannot always get back to you quickly.

 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
